Exploring Events

## Writeup/Lab Overview
This writeup/lab focuses on exploring returned events in Splunk after running a search. It will show how events are displayed on a search page, how event text can be used to expand or narrow a search, and how event and field level actions can help organize data.

## Objectives
- Understand how Splunk displays returned events after a search is run
- Learn how to interact with event text to add or remove terms from a search
- Identify the purpose of Event Actions
- Understand how field and tag actions enrich event data
- Use event exploration to refine a search related to 'failed authentication' activity

## Key Concepts
| Build Event Type | Creates an event type from a search. |
| Event Type | Specific type or useful collection of events. |
| Extract Fields | Opens the field extractor. Allows user to create 'field extractions' from returned events. | 
| Field Extractor | Splunk tool that helps create 'field extractions' from event data. Based on a selected source or source type |
| Show Source | Displays raw source data associated with an event and helps define fields tied to a source or sourcetype |
| edit tag | Add or modify tags associated with an event type or related knowledge object.
| Tags | Help categorize data for easier searching and reporting |

## Exploring Events Write-up
- a list of events is returned when a search is ran
- returned events can be used to 'expand' a search and interact with data
- text searched for is highlighted in the event list
- events are returned in 'reverse chronological order'(newest event is shown first)
- time is normalized in the index to a consistent format
- timestamp is based on 'time zone set in the user account'
- selected fields are shown at the bottom of each event(host, source, sourcetype)
- hovering over text in an event highlights the text
- clicking on highlighted text adds the text to the search job(giving the option to exclude, include or launch a new search of the text)
- each option of the higlighted text has an icon
- clicking the info button of an event shows all 'extracted fields for an event'
- checkmarks designate what fields are shown in an event
- "Event Actions" dropdown provides options:
  - Build Event Type
  - Extract Fields
  - Show Source
- "Field Actions" link allows user to "edit tag"

## Lab Scenario: Filter previous "Failed" Search Job

### Step 1:
- hover over the text "password'
- click on the highlighted text
- click "add to search"(this step adds "password" to the search bar)
- new events are now returned to show "Failed Password" events

### Step 2:
- click on higlighted text "password"
- click "remove from search"
- "password" is now removed from the search job

### Step 3:
- Select the "info button" next to an event to see all "extracted fields for an event"

## Security Relevance
- Explorign individual events helps analysts validate whether suspicious activity is real or noise
- Event-level filtering narrows investigations quickly.
- Field extraction and tagging improve future detections by making data more structured and searchable.

## SOC Analyst Perspective
- Common SOC task: start with broad search, then refine results using values found in returned events
- Event Actions are useful because they turn one-off observations into resuable knowledge objects.
- Better field extraction and tagging can help make investigations faster and more consistent across the team

## Key Takeaways
- Returned events are interactive data that can be used to refine searches
- Event types, extracted fieldss and tags help turn raw events into more useful data
- Event exploration is an important step for more focused investigations
